"Abstract Failure to properly perfect a security interest in computer software can be fatal to the holder of the security interest. Valid and enforceable security interests are important to parties in the financing of transactions, such as a bank lending money secured by computer programs (or other intellectual property) or the seller of acompany who is receiving partial cash and the balance in a note from the buyer secured by the intellectual property assets (and other assets) of the seller's company. The computer software securing the transaction involves several types of intellectual property interests, each of which must be considered in determining the creation and perfection of the security interest and the administration of the collateral."
